      <item>
        <title>Engaging with Virtual Reality</title>
        <description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.gla.ac.uk/schools/computing/researchstudents/markmcgill/&quot;&gt;Mark McGill&lt;/a&gt; and I wanted to solve some of the common issues people had with Virtual Reality headsets. We ran a survey, which showed that one of the key issues to address was enabling people to see their keyboard and other people in the room. We stripped down a webcam, mounted it on an Oculus Rift, and tried out a variety of ways of blending the real and virtual worlds. We found blending based on user engagement, such as when users reach for the keyboard, to work best - people actually managed to type fairly well!
&lt;div class=&quot;embed video YouTube&quot;&gt;&lt;iframe width=&quot;480&quot; height=&quot;270&quot; src=&quot;https://www.youtube.com/embed/SHdfxuh7_GY?feature=oembed&quot; frameborder=&quot;0&quot; allowfullscreen&gt;&lt;/iframe&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

